      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6">Strategic Approach: Minimizing Graduate School Debt</h2>

      <p class="mb-6">
        The graduate students who emerge with minimal debt typically share common characteristics: they begin planning early, pursue multiple funding sources simultaneously, and treat financial aid as an active process rather than passive receipt. They research programs partly based on funding availability, ask directly about support during admissions conversations, and negotiate when circumstances warrant.
      </p>

      <p class="mb-6">
        The funding landscape rewards strategic thinking. A doctoral student who secures an NSF fellowship, supplements with teaching assistantship work, and negotiates institutional support can complete a Ph.D. without borrowing—and potentially accumulate savings from stipend income. A working professional pursuing an MBA can leverage employer tuition benefits to cover significant costs while maintaining income. Even students who must borrow can minimize debt through careful program selection, aggressive scholarship pursuit, and disciplined borrowing limited to actual need.
      </p>

      <p class="mb-10">
        The key insight: graduate funding is not solely determined by financial need or academic merit. It results from systematic effort across multiple dimensions—identifying opportunities, meeting deadlines, presenting compelling applications, and advocating effectively for support. Students who approach funding with this mindset consistently achieve better outcomes than equally qualified peers who treat financial aid as an administrative afterthought.
      </p>

